Introduction to ncaahoopR

Jim Albert

1/23/2020

Introduction

ncaahoopR is a R package for scraping and graphing play-by-play men college basketball data

Load packages

We begin by loading the tidyverse and ncaahoopR packages.

library(tidyverse)
library(ncaahoopR)

Scrape data for one game

To begin, let’s scrape the data for the exciting BGSU-Ohio contest of January 11, 2020.

I find the description of the game on ESPN:

https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/game?gameId=401172643

Looking at the html address, I see the game id is 401172643

I can scrape this game by the get_pbp_game() function.

d <- get_pbp_game(401172643)

Here are a few rows of this data frame.

Game flow chart

The game_flow() function scrapes data for a game and plots the scores of both teams as a function of the minutes elapsed.

game_flow(401172643, "green", "brown")

Win probability chart

The gg_wp_chart() scrapes the data and shows the win probabilities for each team as a function of the minutes elapsed.

gg_wp_chart(401172643, "green", "brown")

Shot charts

For many of the top league games (unfortunately not MAC games) shot location data is available. The game_shot_chart() graphs the shots for both teams. Here is an illustration (this is the Duke-Kentucky game of November 6, 2018).

game_shot_chart(game_id = 401082669)
